        "$:/language/Help/fetch": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/fetch",
            "description": "Fetch tiddlers from wiki by URL",
            "text": "Fetch one or more files over HTTP/HTTPS, and import the tiddlers matching a filter, optionally transforming the incoming titles.\n\n```\n--fetch file <url> <import-filter> <transform-filter>\n--fetch files <url-filter> <import-filter> <transform-filter>\n--fetch raw-file <url> <transform-filter>\n--fetch raw-files <url-filter> <transform-filter>\n```\n\nThe \"file\" and \"files\" variants fetch the specified files and attempt to import the tiddlers within them (the same processing as if the files were dragged into the browser window). The \"raw-file\" and \"raw-files\" variants fetch the specified files and then store the raw file data in tiddlers, without applying the import logic.\n\nWith the \"file\" and \"raw-file\" variants only a single file is fetched and the first parameter is the URL of the file to read.\n\nWith the \"files\" and \"raw-files\" variants, multiple files are fetched and the first parameter is a filter yielding a list of URLs of the files to read. For example, given a set of tiddlers tagged \"remote-server\" that have a field \"url\" the filter `[tag[remote-server]get[url]]` will retrieve all the available URLs.\n\nFor the \"file\" and \"files\" variants, the `<import-filter>` parameter specifies a filter determining which tiddlers are imported. It defaults to `[all[tiddlers]]` if not provided.\n\nFor all variants, the `<transform-filter>` parameter specifies an optional filter that transforms the titles of the imported tiddlers. For example, `[addprefix[$:/myimports/]]` would add the prefix `$:/myimports/` to each title.\n\nPreceding the `--fetch` command with `--verbose` will output progress information during the import.\n\nNote that TiddlyWiki will not fetch an older version of an already loaded plugin.\n\nThe following example retrieves all the non-system tiddlers from https://tiddlywiki.com and saves them to a JSON file:\n\n```\ntiddlywiki --verbose --fetch file \"https://tiddlywiki.com/\" \"[!is[system]]\" \"\" --rendertiddler \"$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile\" output.json text/plain \"\" exportFilter \"[!is[system]]\"\n```\n\nThe following example retrieves the \"favicon\" file from tiddlywiki.com and saves it in a file called \"output.ico\". Note that the intermediate tiddler \"Icon Tiddler\" is quoted in the \"--fetch\" command because it is being used as a transformation filter to replace the default title, while there are no quotes for the \"--savetiddler\" command because it is being used directly as a title.\n\n```\ntiddlywiki --verbose --fetch raw-file \"https://tiddlywiki.com/favicon.ico\" \"[[Icon Tiddler]]\" --savetiddler \"Icon Tiddler\" output.ico\n```\n\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/help": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/help",
            "description": "Display help for TiddlyWiki commands",
            "text": "Displays help text for a command:\n\n```\n--help [<command>]\n```\n\nIf the command name is omitted then a list of available commands is displayed.\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/import": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/import",
            "description": "Import tiddlers from a file",
            "text": "Import tiddlers from TiddlyWiki (`.html`), `.tiddler`, `.tid`, `.json` or other local files. The deserializer must be explicitly specified, unlike the `load` command which infers the deserializer from the file extension.\n\n```\n--import <filepath> <deserializer> [<title>] [<encoding>]\n```\n\nThe deserializers in the core include:\n\n* application/javascript\n* application/json\n* application/x-tiddler\n* application/x-tiddler-html-div\n* application/x-tiddlers\n* text/html\n* text/plain\n\nThe title of the imported tiddler defaults to the filename.\n\nThe encoding defaults to \"utf8\", but can be \"base64\" for importing binary files.\n\nNote that TiddlyWiki will not import an older version of an already loaded plugin.\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/init": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/init",
            "description": "Initialise a new wiki folder",
            "text": "Initialise an empty [[WikiFolder|WikiFolders]] with a copy of the specified edition.\n\n```\n--init <edition> [<edition> ...]\n```\n\nFor example:\n\n```\ntiddlywiki ./MyWikiFolder --init empty\n```\n\nNote:\n\n* The wiki folder directory will be created if necessary\n* The \"edition\" defaults to ''empty''\n* The init command will fail if the wiki folder is not empty\n* The init command removes any `includeWikis` definitions in the edition's `tiddlywiki.info` file\n* When multiple editions are specified, editions initialised later will overwrite any files shared with earlier editions (so, the final `tiddlywiki.info` file will be copied from the last edition)\n* `--editions` returns a list of available editions\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/listen": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/listen",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki",
            "text": "Serves a wiki over HTTP.\n\nThe listen command uses NamedCommandParameters:\n\n```\n--listen [<name>=<value>]...\n```\n\nAll parameters are optional with safe defaults, and can be specified in any order. The recognised parameters are:\n\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''path-prefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n* ''port'' - port number on which to listen; non-numeric values are interpreted as a system environment variable from which the port number is extracted (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''credentials'' - pathname of credentials CSV file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''anon-username'' - the username for signing edits for anonymous users\n* ''username'' - optional username for basic authentication\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''authenticated-user-header'' - optional name of header to be used for trusted authentication\n* ''readers'' - comma separated list of principals allowed to read from this wiki\n* ''writers'' - comma separated list of principals allowed to write to this wiki\n* ''csrf-disable'' - set to \"yes\" to disable CSRF checks (defaults to \"no\")\n* ''root-tiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\")\n* ''root-render-type'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''root-serve-type'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''tls-cert'' - pathname of TLS certificate file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''tls-key'' - pathname of TLS key file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''debug-level'' - optional debug level; set to \"debug\" to view request details (defaults to \"none\")\n* ''gzip'' - set to \"yes\" to enable gzip compression for some http endpoints (defaults to \"no\")\n\nFor information on opening up your instance to the entire local network, and possible security concerns, see the WebServer tiddler at TiddlyWiki.com.\n\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/load": {

        "$:/language/Help/render": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/render",
            "description": "Renders individual tiddlers to files",
            "text": "Render individual tiddlers identified by a filter and save the results to the specified files.\n\nOptionally, the title of a template tiddler can be specified. In this case, instead of directly rendering each tiddler, the template tiddler is rendered with the \"currentTiddler\" variable set to the title of the tiddler that is being rendered.\n\nA name and value for an additional variable may optionally also be specified.\n\n```\n--render <tiddler-filter> [<filename-filter>] [<render-type>] [<template>] [<name>] [<value>]\n```\n\n* ''tiddler-filter'': A filter identifying the tiddler(s) to be rendered\n* ''filename-filter'': Optional filter transforming tiddler titles into pathnames. If omitted, defaults to `[is[tiddler]addsuffix[.html]]`, which uses the unchanged tiddler title as the filename\n* ''render-type'': Optional render type: `text/html` (the default) returns the full HTML text and `text/plain` just returns the text content (ie it ignores HTML tags and other unprintable material)\n* ''template'': Optional template through which each tiddler is rendered\n* ''name'': Name of optional variable\n* ''value'': Value of optional variable\n\nBy default, the filename is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nNotes:\n\n* The output directory is not cleared of any existing files\n* Any missing directories in the path to the filename are automatically created.\n* When referring to a tiddler with spaces in its title, take care to use both the quotes required by your shell and also TiddlyWiki's double square brackets : `--render \"[[Motovun Jack.jpg]]\"`\n* The filename filter is evaluated with the selected items being set to the title of the tiddler currently being rendered, allowing the title to be used as the basis for computing the filename. For example `[encodeuricomponent[]addprefix[static/]]` applies URI encoding to each title, and then adds the prefix `static/`\n* The `--render` command is a more flexible replacement for both the `--rendertiddler` and `--rendertiddlers` commands, which are deprecated\n\nExamples:\n\n* `--render \"[!is[system]]\" \"[encodeuricomponent[]addprefix[tiddlers/]addsuffix[.html]]\"` -- renders all non-system tiddlers as files in the subdirectory \"tiddlers\" with URL-encoded titles and the extension HTML\n\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/rendertiddler": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/rendertiddler",
            "description": "Render an individual tiddler as a specified ContentType",
            "text": "(Note: The `--rendertiddler` command is deprecated in favour of the new, more flexible `--render` command)\n\nRender an individual tiddler as a specified ContentType, defaulting to `text/html` and save it to the specified filename.\n\nOptionally the title of a template tiddler can be specified, in which case the template tiddler is rendered with the \"currentTiddler\" variable set to the tiddler that is being rendered (the first parameter value).\n\nA name and value for an additional variable may optionally also be specified.\n\n```\n--rendertiddler <title> <filename> [<type>] [<template>] [<name>] [<value>]\n```\n\nBy default, the filename is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nAny missing directories in the path to the filename are automatically created.\n\nFor example, the following command saves all tiddlers matching the filter `[tag[done]]` to a JSON file titled `output.json` by employing the core template `$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile`.\n\n```\n--rendertiddler \"$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile\" output.json text/plain \"\" exportFilter \"[tag[done]]\"\n```\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/rendertiddlers": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/rendertiddlers",
            "description": "Render tiddlers matching a filter to a specified ContentType",
            "text": "(Note: The `--rendertiddlers` command is deprecated in favour of the new, more flexible `--render` command)\n\nRender a set of tiddlers matching a filter to separate files of a specified ContentType (defaults to `text/html`) and extension (defaults to `.html`).\n\n```\n--rendertiddlers <filter> <template> <pathname> [<type>] [<extension>] [\"noclean\"]\n```\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--rendertiddlers [!is[system]] $:/core/templates/static.tiddler.html ./static text/plain\n```\n\nBy default, the pathname is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nAny files in the target directory are deleted unless the ''noclean'' flag is specified. The target directory is recursively created if it is missing.\n"

        "$:/language/Help/server": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/server",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki (deprecated in favour of the new listen command)",
            "text": "Legacy command to serve a wiki over HTTP.\n\n```\n--server <port> <root-tiddler> <root-render-type> <root-serve-type> <username> <password> <host> <path-prefix> <debug-level>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''port'' - port number on which to listen; non-numeric values are interpreted as a system environment variable from which the port number is extracted (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''root-tiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\")\n* ''root-render-type'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''root-serve-type'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''username'' - the default username for signing edits\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''path-prefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n* ''debug-level'' - optional debug level; set to \"debug\" to view request details (defaults to \"none\")\n\nIf the password parameter is specified then the browser will prompt the user for the username and password. Note that the password is transmitted in plain text so this implementation should only be used on a trusted network or over HTTPS.\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n\nThe username and password can be specified as empty strings if you need to set the hostname or pathprefix and don't want to require a password.\n\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html \"\" \"\" 192.168.0.245\n```\n\nUsing an address like this exposes your system to the local network. For information on opening up your instance to the entire local network, and possible security concerns, see the WebServer tiddler at TiddlyWiki.com.\n\nTo run multiple TiddlyWiki servers at the same time you'll need to put each one on a different port. It can be useful to use an environment variable to pass the port number to the Node.js process. This example references an environment variable called \"MY_PORT_NUMBER\":\n\n```\n--server MY_PORT_NUMBER $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n"
        },

fluid-fixed






classic






<<<
Cognitive task analysis are concerned with the underlying thought process associated with performing a task.
<<<

Not only what we can see, but more importantly what we can not see.

Steps:

# ''Collect preliminary knowledge ''(might watch user using GPS)
# ''Identify knowledge representations'' (what kind of things does a user need to know to complete their task?  Types or structures of knowledge... does this task involve a series of steps to do in a certain order?.... a web of knowledge?)
# ''Apply focused knowledge elicitation methods. ''(recognize what the user actually knows, identify all the steps the user must take, the knowledge they must have in mind to take those actions, interruptions that can change their thought processes, sensory experience of the user... identify whats going on in their heads or environment)
# ''Analyze and verify the data acquired'' (confirming with the people we observe that our understanding is correct, present user our results, attempt to formalize it into structures that can be compared and summarized across multiple data gathering methods)
# ''Format results for intended application'' (show what the user was thinking, feeling, and remembering at any given time and make those relationships really explicit)

Results:
[img[High level design of driving to destination]]







Large tasks are often made up of many smaller tasks.

Ex: Cognitive model of driving.... each task can be broken up into smaller tasks that can be used in different contexts.

Ex: Purchasing online.  Borrowed metaphors - cart from real world.  We actually have a sub task of 'Checkout' which includes the steps:

# Enter billing info
# Enter card info
# Review purchase

Allows designer to abstract over process and focus on what might make their site unique.






Sequence of thoughts inside users head, special attention to what she needs to remember at each step of the process.

Thoughts using keypad...

* Get key out to unlock door
* Open door
* Close door behind
* Need to disable alarm before it goes off
* What is the code
* Press the correct sequence of buttons
* Confirm it is disarmed.

Thoughts using keyfob:

* Get key out to unlock door
* Open door
* Close door behind
* Need to disable alarm before it goes off
* Press the disarm button on keyfob
* Confirm it is disarmed.

With keyfob - she had option of disarming before even entering... but has to remember.  The keypad beeps at her till she turns it off so she doesn't have to remember... but she has to remember the keycode.

''Realization''... why does she need to press key at all?  Why doesn't it just detect that she's coming in with keychain her pocket?






Strengths:

* ''Emphasize mental processes ''(what goes on inside users head)
* ''Formal enough to be used for interface design'' for comparisons in mode alternatives and more

Weakness:

* ''Time intensive to perform.''  Involve talking to multiple experts, then systematically analyzing the data.
* ''May deemphasize context ''- by zooming in on individual thought processes, risks deemphasizing details that are out in the world.
* ''Ill suited for novices'' - well suited to experts who understand their mental processes.






[img[Examples of other task analysis frameworks]]

''KLM, TLM, MHP'' - capture even finer grain actions for estimating performance speed.

''CPM-GOMS ''- focuses on parallel tasks

''NGOMSL'' - provides natural language interface for interacting with GOMS models

''CDM'' - puts focus on places where critical decisions occur.

''TKS'' - focuses on the nature of human's knowledge

''CFM'' - focuses on complexity

''Applied CTA, Skill-Based CTA'' - focus on gathering information necessary to create a cognitive model

''Production Systems'' - Common in artificial intellegence.






* Human Information processor model
* Builds off of the processor model

The G.O.M.S. abbreviation stands for:

* G = Goals
* O = Operators
* M = Methods
* S = Selection Rules

Visualized:

[img[Screen Shot 2020-06-24 at 8.14.24 PM.png]]











!!Need to transfer information to coworker

[img[Sending Information to Friend]]

''Selection Rules: ''Time sensitive - do it in person

Execute series of operators, end result is information is transmitted.

!!Navigation
[img[GOMS Navigation Example]]

Selection Rules - not time sensitive, use scenic route.  Rush hour use highway.






Goals: Entering home  and alarm re-enabled.

Operators: Keypad - (Unlock door, open door, close door, enter code, press arm)
Operators Keychain - (Press disarm on keychain, unlock, open door, close door, press arm)

Methods: Keypad, Key chain.

Selection Rules: If we have our hands full -> use keypad, otherwise use keychain.

[img[Security GOMS Model]]







''idea:'' Distributed cognition is deeply related to the idea of cognitive load.

Artifacts in distributed cognition add additional cognitive resources.  Same cognitive load is distributed along additional resources.

GPS offloads cognitive load of navigation.  Cruise Control offloads cognitive load of maintaining speed.






Weakness:

* Doesn't address complexity
* Assumes user is an expert (doesn't account for user error)

Strengths:

* Formalize user interaction into steps (measure time it takes each step)







Types of GOMS models:

* Vanilla GOMS
* KLM-GOMS (keystroke-level-model)
* CMN-GOMS
* NGOMSL

!!KLM-GOMS (keystroke-level-model)
Designer specifies operator and execution times for an action and sums them to find the complexity of an interaction.

!!CMN-GOMS (Card, Moran, and Newel)
Hierarchy of goals and sub-goals, and ability to choose between multiple goals.  Includes very low-level goals.  Authors are using it to identify complexity that can be cut out.

!!NGOMSL (Natural GOMS Language)
Natural language form of GOMS that leads itself to human interpretation.  

!!GOMS Models in General
Helps us identify areas we might be asking too much of the user - example of overtaxing working memory.







Tips:

# Focus on small moment-to-moment goals
# Nest goals, not operators.  Operators are 'atoms' of the actual actions that must be performed.
# Differentiate descriptive and prescriptive.  Identify what people do (descriptive) or should do (prescriptive)
# Assign costs to operators - how long certain operations take (ex time).
# Use GOMS to trim waste - allows you to visualize unneccesary operators, and simplify the interface.






''Cognitive Task Analysis'' - puts higher emphasis on things like memory, attention, and cognitive load.  Adopts more of the predictor view of the human's role in the system.






Old battle in psychology:

''Processor Model <--> Behaviorism'' (things that can be observed, emphasizes behavior as a product of stimuli and the environment)
   

''Predictor Model <--> Cognitivism''
(An approach to psychology that emphasizes internal thought processes)






''Social Cognition'' - social connections create systems that can, together, accomplish task.  Also concerned with the cognitive underpinnings of social interactions themselves.

''idea'': how perception, memory, learning relate to social phenomena.












''Question'': How to create social gaming system that protects against perceptions?

Alerting when other are also interested -> getting at the idea of an 'in-group' - your behaviors are only seen by others who share them, so are in no position to judge them.






''def'' - humans as improvisors.  Not the kinds of problems that people have solved before.  Novel situational problems.  Task is what we do, not what we design.

# Examine the interface we design within the context in which they're used.
# Understand the task the user performs grows out of the interaction with the interface.
# The task doesn't exist until the user gets started, and once they start, they define the task.










remember - recognition is easier than recall.

This happens because memory is ''context dependent''.

example: Mom asking favors, she can remember list because they are part of a broader narrative... rather than things on a list.








<<<
The first, adopted by researchers in Cognitive Science, views the organization and significance of action as derived from plans"
<<<

Users make plans, and users carry out those plans.


<<<
The second view, drawn from recent work in social science, treats plans as derivative from situated action.
<<<
People simply act in the world, and plans are what we derive from those actions.  Instead of plans dictating actions, plans are interpretations of actions.

--> Forget the history of actions that led the user to a certain screen and ask just, "Once they're here, how do they know what to do next?"






''def'' - a massive and well developed set of theories regarding interaction between various pieces of an activity

Predates HCI, where we get the idea of interacting through an interface.

* Generalizes the unit of analysis not at the 'task' but rather at the 'activity' - interested not only in what they are doing, but why they are doing it and what it means to them.

--> Designs will be different if users are using a system if they are required to or if they choose to.

--> create low level operations from higher level actions.

--> actions by user can move up and down hierarchy.









<<<
Activity theory offers a set of perspectives on human activity and a set of concepts for describing the activity.  This, it seems to me, is exactly what HCI research needs as we struggle to understand and describe 'context', 'situation', and 'practice.
<<<









<<<
Distributed cognition suggests models of cognition should be extended to outside the mind
<<<

''Idea:'' Expand definition of intelligence from a single mind --> mind equipped with other minds and artifacts and the relationships among them.

''Example:'' Using paper+pencil to add numbers.  System comprised of user+pen+paper -> cognition was distributed amongst these artifacts.







''idea:'' we usually ascribe 'remembering' to humans, i.e. computers don't remember.

The paper title tells us the entire system of pilot+sensors+interfaces among them that do the remembering... not just the human pilot.






When a plane is descending for landing, there are a number of different wing configurations the pilot needs to make at different speeds

Remembering a sequence of speeds - high cognitive load.

How do they do this?

* Pilots have pages with speeds of decent based on different parameters.
* Cockpit has booklet of such pages
* Pilots responsible for ''deliberation''
* Booklet of speeds form the l''ong-term memory''
* Before decent, pilot pull out paper and pin it up - this is the ''short term memory.''
* Pilots mark on speedometer the different speeds - "speed bugs" - like the ''working memory''







Morgan paying bills manually, with two piles.

-----

The two piles serve as ''external memory ''of the bills Morgan has already paid.  She doesn't have to keep track.

The bills themselves ''remember'' a lot of information like amounts and destination.

The checkbook takes care of the ''record keeping task'' for Morgan since they create carbon copies.

The pen is involved in ''communicating with these systems ''so it is involved in our cognitive system as well.






Setting up computer desk with multiple monitors:

* Having calendar displayed is a way of ''offloading daily schedule''.
* Clock as distributed cognition since it offloads the task of keeping track of the passage of time.






Email is an external memory of all communications via email and tasks that are waiting on me to move forward.






Before GPS - we used distributed cognition in the form of passenger announcing directions.

Jira - breaks down tasks into multiple pieces that can be distributed among multiple people.  Manages distributing tasks among team.






!! Types of Evaluation

Qualitative Evaluation:

* Emphasizes the totality of a phenomenon
* What do they like, don't like
* What is easy, what is hard.

Empirical Evaluation:

* Evaluation based on numeric summaries or observations of a phenomenon
* Controlled experiments
* Evaluate results quantitatively
* Want to make sure we have addressed qualitative feedback first since we will need more participants.

Predictive Evaluation:

* Evaluation based on systematic application of pre-established principles and heuristics.
* Evaluation without users
* Not favorite type of evaluation for HCI
* User testing is complicated and expensive, so this gives us way to do simple evaluation on a continual basis.






def - ''reliability'' - Whether a measure consistently returns the same results for the same phenomenon.

ex: Asking Amanda for time gives same answer.

def - ''validity'' - Whether a measure's result actually reflects the underlying phenomenon.

ex: Asking Amanda for time, was reliable, but incorrect as time was different.

def - ''generalizability'' - Whether a measure's results can be used to predict phenomena beyond what is measured.

def - ''precision'' - a measure of how specific (or precise) a measurement is.

ex: Amanda says it 1:30 but it is actually 1:31:31.  Amanda isn't wrong but is less precise.






What to evaluate:

* ''Efficiency'' (the time it takes to accomplish a task)
* ''Accuracy'' (how many errors do users commit while accomplishing a task)
* ''Learnability'' (sit user down, how long does it take user to hit level of expertise)
* ''Memorability'' (refers to a user's ability to remember how to user an interface over time)
* ''Satisfaction'' (user's enjoyment of system, or cognitive load of system)

--> It is important at the beginning to clearly articulate at the beginning what you're evaluating, what data you're gathering, and what analysis you will use.






Early in process: Qualitative, Predictive

Later in process: Empirical

# Keep prototypes easy to change
# Make it clear its a prototype
# Be creative
# Evaluate risks
# Prototype for feedback






Users like to group items spatially and often prefer to deal with information by creating physical piles of paper.

!User Interviews
!! Use of folders
* random, color coded, alphabetical
* "folderize to keep things neat... there's no hierarchy in there because building a hierarchy takes too much time"

!! Piles: A less rigid categorization system

* Separate piles for each subject
* Piles for incoming information not to be dealt with immediately
* no need for detailed categorization, easily reordered
* Piles could be reshuffled, broken into new piles
* Stacking material at different angles
* Newer items at top

!! Piles: self-revealing, browseable

* Allowed users to recognize particular items
* Contents of pile could be inferred from the outside.

!! Assistance with information management

* Assistants acted as a filter, passing along urgent material, and removing junk.
* Reorganizing filing system by assistant would often happen in collaboration

! From observation to design sketch
!! User-created piles
* User would create pile of digital objects

!! System created piles
*System would assemble these piles using scripts

!! Support for browsing
* gestural inputs to invoke browsing methods (spread out, viewing cone..)

!! Managing Piles
* Organize by date, color coding label, create new piles

!Results
!! Piling models
* "document centered" vs "pile centered"
* Wanted to be able to add selected group of items to a pile, name piles, apply ordering based on date, size, name, and kind

!! Initiated Browsing
* Participants preferred double clicking (9 out of 10)
* Gestures were non-intuitive and somewhat ambiguous
* Users preferred the spread out view since they could view multiple items at once which supported recognition and comparison

!! Cone Representations

* The side by side (2nd option below) was preferred by users.
[img[Cone View]]
















Relationship between the properties of an object and the capabilities of the agent that determine how the object could be used.

* Ex: A chair affords support for sitting, lifting.
* Ex: Glass affords transparency but blocks passage (birds crash into it as it hides its ability to block... antiaffordances)

Door with push bar affords pushing, door with handle affords pulling.

Accidental affordances - putting trash at top of wall becomes strong [[Signifiers]].












Useful metaphor:

* 5 slots each capable of holding 1 item
* Each decays with a half life of 15 seconds
* Most information lost from stimulation as new information takes up slots

<<<
Applying what is known from science to the design and construction of machines.
<<<

Goals:

* Understand the fundamental principles behind human action and performance that are relevant to the engineering principles of design
* Devise systems that are easy/pleasant to use, systems that are fun, 
* "pleasurable engagement"


__An analysis of task complexity__ - even simple controls can produce confusing mental models

__Physical Variables__ - Physical systems to be manipulated.  Ex: shower knobs

# Mapping Problems - Which is hot, cold, which direction increases flow
# Ease of control
# Evaluation

Even simple tasks involve large number of aspects.

* IMDB
* OpenStreetMap

* BBC Animals & Biomes
* MusicBrains
* GeoNames
* FilmTrust
* LinkedMB (Linked Move Database)
* Yago
* Wordnet






Command Line Interfaces - 1 input channel.   

Direct Manipulation Systems (Xerox 8100):      

* Multiple input channels.     
* Continuous (ex slider).     
* Discrete - Drop down menu.  
* Accept input in any order.   
* Event driven programming
* New programming language (SmallTalk)
* Software architecture - MVC
* Closed software system - only run programs developed by Xerox


Menus === Recognition.   

Commands === Recall.    

(Recognition preferred over recall)

The most profound technologies are those that dissapear

def: Using computers to support people working

* Same time same place. 
* Same time different place
* Different time different place
* Different time different place






''definition ''- a simplified explanation of how something works.  Conceptional models are valuable only as long as the assumptions hold.  Conceptual models are informed from the device, passed from person to person, or from a manual.

Scissors provide a clear conceptual model of how to use them... there are holes to put fingers into.

Conceptual models provide understanding, predicting how things behave.  Incorrect conceptual models (refrigerator controls) can be frustrating.

Everyday things - simple conceptual models.


<<<
Conceptional model provides the scaffolding upon which to bind the bridges across the gulf --> important during learning and trouble shooting, experts can do with out them
<<<

Note:  Mental models are neither complete or accurate but they function to guide much of human behavior.

The user model (inside the user's head) is different from the design model (inside the designers head).... it is influenced by the documentation, and system image.

The primary task of designer is to construct the system image - realizing everything the user interacts with that helps the user form that image - knobs, dials, keyboard displays, documentation (including instruction manuals), help facilities, text input, output, error messages.

Good examples of system image:

* Spreadsheet programs
* Stack calculator
* Office desk metaphor of Xerox Star and Lisa

Needfinding -> Design alternatives- > Protoyping -> Evaluation -> Needfinding

A single prototype corresponds to a single iteration through the cycle. 






''def: Trade-off ''- Any design virtues along one dimension that cause a defficiency along another dimension.

Prototypical Trade-off: Information vs Time
(more information displayed, decreases workspace)






Part of [[The Design of Everyday Things by Don Norman]]

---

<<<
It is relatively easy to design for the situation where everything
goes well ... The tricky part is to design for when things go wrong
<<<

--> Even simple checks for reasonableness would have stopped all these errors.

* Understand the causes of error and design to minimize those causes
* Do sensibility checks
* Make it possible to reverse actions - to "undo" them -  or make it harder to do things that cannot be reversed
* Make it easier for people to discover the errors that do occur, and make them easier to correct
* Don't treat the action as an error, rather, try to help the person complete the action properly.  Think of the action as an approximation to what is desired.

--> Most systems make it difficult to resume after an interruption. To resume, it might be necessary to go to the previous state of the activity.

--> Doing two tasks at once takes longer than the sum of the times it would take to do each alone.

--> The design of warning signals is surprisingly complex. They
have to be loud or bright enough to be noticed, but not so loud or
bright that they become annoying distractions. 

Design Lessons:

* Adding constraints to block errors
* Allow undo
* Confirmation and error messages
* Make the item being acted upon more prominent
* Sensibility checks
* Ensure the actions and their controls are as dissimilar as possible or at lease physically far apart.
* Perceptible feedback
* Design redundancy and layers of defence

!! Most errors don't cause accidents - The Swiss Cheese Model

[img[Swiss Cheese Model of Accidents]]

def - ''resilience engineering'' - goal of designing systems, procedures, management, and training of people so they are able to respond to problems as they arise.

Deliberately shutting down critical facilities to ensure that the backup systems and redundancies actually work.

!! The Paradox of Automation

The paradox is
that automation can take over the dull, dreary tasks, but fail with
the complex ones.


<<<
Difficulties arise when we do not think of people and machines
as collaborative systems, but assign whatever tasks can be automated to the machines and leave the rest to people.

Verbal Prototypes:

* Revisable during interaction

Paper Prototypes:

* Revisable during interaction
* Disguises superficial details

Card Prototypes:

* Revisable during interaction
* Disguises superficial details
* Simulates user interaction

Wizard of oz

* Revisable during interaction
* Disguises superficial details
* Simulates user interaction
* Allows mobility during evaluation

Wireframing

* Simulates user interaction
* Easily distributable to remote users
* Supports prototying look and feel

Physical Prototypes

* Simulates user interaction
* Supports prototying look and feel
* Allows mobility during evaluation






People pushing button on elevator or pedestrian crossing signal. => missing feedback.

Feedback communicates result of an action.  Feedback must be immediate and informative.  Too much feedback can be more annoying than too little.  Feedback is essential but it has to be done correctly.

Question: Is it possible that volunteers could be constantly be updating an online knowledge graph?

We have to accept human behavior the way it is, not the other way around.  Design systems for human __error__.






HCI - Studying the force underlying the advances that migrate into products and process that people use.  Included in the study of HCI - psychology (cognitive and experiemental), sociology, anthropology, cognitive science, and linquistics.

* Universal design








Part of [[The Design of Everyday Things by Don Norman]]

---

* Most industrial accidents are caused by human errors: estimates range between 75 and 95 percent.  
* Are people incompetent?  No, its a design problem

!! Causes for errors:
* Staying alert for hours at a time
* Providing precise, accurate control specifications
* All while multitasking
*Interruptions are common reason for error.
* The attitude of people towards errors.
* Time stress along with environmental factors.

Blaming people doesn't fix the problem as another human will make the same mistake.

def: ''Root Cause Analysis'' - investigate the accident until the single underlying cause is found.

Most accidents have multiple things that go wrong... aka the //Swiss cheese model of accidents//

<<<
One big problem is that the natural tendency to blame someone
for an error is even shared by those who made the error, who
often agree that it was their fault. 
<<<

def: ''Deliberate Violations'' - people intentionally violate procedures and regulations.

--> When employees feel it necessary to violate the rules in order to get the job done, and as a result, succeed, they will probably be congratulated and rewarded.

Part of [[Human-Computer Interaction by Scott MacKenzie]]

---

* Although the time to complete a task can enhance or hinder by degree, ''errors only hinder''.
* Broken expectations sooner or later cause errors.
* Often called //user errors// but are more accurately called //design-induced errors//

High Cost Errors occur with low frequency.  They receive a lot of attention and get dealt with.  Next designers shift to fixing less costly errors, like CAPS_LOCK.  But the little errors slip through.

!! Examples:
* Save changes? vs Discard changes?  Disastrous if data is discarded.
* Caps lock on password form fields (input is visually obscured).  Fixed with caps lock alerts.
* Select text at end of page initiates scrolling.
* First field on page does not immediately have focus, like on username/password.
* User may be looking at keyboard and may not know focus automatically advanced to next field.


[img[Example of bad save changes]]

[img[Example of caps lock alert]]

[img[Cost of Error vs Frequency of Error]]







Invented by Douglas Engelbart.  On screen tracking, allowing text to be selected.    

* Development of point-select & point-and-click.   
* User Study - measured onset of cursor movement, movement time, and error rate    
* Xerox Parc further refined the mouse with a graphical user interface (GUI)    
* Took 20 years to be commercialized    






Manipulation of geometric objects using light pen.    
First direct manipulation interface:    

* Visibility of objects    
* Incremental action    
* Rapid feedback    
* Reversibility    
* Exploration    
* Syntactic correctness    






Relationship between elements of two sets of items (borrowed from mathematics).

When using spatial mapping, it is easier to determine how to use them.  Provides a clear way of remembering and understanding mappings.

Groupings and proximity are important principles from Gestalt Psychology






<<<
One of the most common ways to learn and adapt is through physical analogy 
<<<
* Physical analogies are examples of //mental models//, aka //conceptual models//
* Ex: desktop metaphor

def: ''Implementation models'' - impose on the user a set of interactions that follow the inner workings of an application.  

''Note'': Implementation models should be avoided.

When viewing the Corel draw menu, can the user figure out the functionality based on the icon and tool tip alone?

[img[Example of the Correl Draw menu]]

<<<
Each user learns the smallest set of features that he needs to get his work
done, and he abandons the rest
<<<

* Compass is also an example of a mental model.  Allowing user to describe //north// as up and //west// for left
* Clocks provide metaphor as a way to describe the location of things - ex: 'Obstacle ahead at 2 o'clock'

[img[Other examples of metaphors]]






''Note'': All prototypes have to be at the same level at the same time.  Different designs may be in different levels of fidelity.

Design top-down or bottom-up






Discoverability - Figuring out what actions are possible.  Relevant components must be visible and communicate the correct message.

Draw out the interface on paper.  Pretty obvious that not asking about font/colors/etc.

Very easy to immediately revise.

You can also prototype user interaction using paper designs.






note: It doesn't actually have to work!

Lots of elements you can test without implementation.

Test general idea of using keyfob - running while holding it, testing holding it in hand, etc






Hiking Trail Recommendations:

* Takes into account seasonal variations
* Takes into account weather variations
* Takes into account where the person is located
* Takes into account the user's preferences

Allows a user to plan a hike

* Potential dates
* Weather forcast
* Possible people going
* Equipment checklist
* Fee/Licenses needed

Time is an important way to filter information.... users want to get an idea of how long it will take to travel and complete an activity... rather than the distance.






Systems are deemed useful because they offer powerful tools that the user is able to apply constructively and creatively with understanding.

''Examples:'' Smalltalk, Xerox, Unix, Interlisp & LIsp, DWIM (Do what I mean), Spreadsheets, Steamer, Bill's pinball construction set


<<<
Systems shouldn't take too much control from users
<<<

Proper level of a tool:

Primitive <---------> Specialized







[[Brainstorming Ideas]]






In this prototype, the design is like a 'slot machine'.  There is an animation of 'rotating' possibilities of possible trails.  Instead of the different icons that are shown for a slot machine, there are images/descriptions of possible hiking trails.  The user selects the ones they want to keep, and these show up at the bottom in a 'tray' of potential hikes.  

The user then 'pulls the lever' which is just a digital animation, and the screen animates the same way a slot machine is, but now shows 5 new possibilities, excluding any option shown previously.  The 5 new options use information about what the user previously selected/exluded to show new options to the user.  The user then selects anything that looks interesting, and the process repeats.

Once the user has identified a minimum number of interesting options, the user could quit and see the options that are recommended based on their current selected set.... OR... the user could keep going as long as they want, knowing that the recommendation engine will get better.  

This might incorporate some game mechanic elements that allow the recommendation engine to quickly learn the items that the user is interested in.










Idea: user can converse with alexa which generates hiking recommendations.






idea: The user can browse hikes, but they can mark hikes that look interesting or have completed already.  Their browsing history, and the hikes they marked as interesting provide signals to the recommendation engine.






Idea: Types of animals vary wildly between different biomes.

Ask the user to identify animals and/or plants that they have seen in real life on a hike.  This will help identify where the user has been even if they don't know the name of the hike.






Hiking gear might be a signal of the experience level of the user.






Allow the user to select hikes that they have already experienced.
Then generate a list of recommendations based on that list.






Idea: Hold phone, and hold it up towards horizon.

Phone app will tell you hikes in that direction.  Scrolling on the device allows you to zoom out/zoom in.

Possibilities are shown to the user






Idea: create list of super unique and different type of hikes.

The user completes the hikes, and uploads their review/preferences.

The list is chosen so that a wide range of experiences is available, so that the recommendation engine can better understand where the user's prefered experience is.






Idea: social game that users can plant a flag, that their friends can go 'capture'

Leverages social recommendations to understand the types of hikes that people like within certain social networks.






Idea: Ask and connect to the user's facebook profile.  Download information about the user that is helpful for generating recommendations.






* In this prototype, the interface is just a chat app on Facebook.
* You 'talk' to the chat app, and it learns more about the user.






Idea: Generate grouping of similar hikes that the user can try out.

Example: 
- 3 hikes with waterfalls
- 5 hikes near railroads
- 3 urban hikes near you
- 5 county high points near you

The user has incentive to complete the hike, and upload their expriences.






Useful if the user hasn't gone hiking before.  The user can go out and try the hike, then report back to the reporting engine how it went.






With this idea, users sign up to receive a weekly email of 5 ideas of a hiking trail they could discover on the weekend.  Background analytics are generated when users click on the ideas in the email.  They can also mention if they like the hike, didn't like the hike, and submit other ideas.






Group hikes into popular categories that the user can browse.






* This is a prototype idea on how to discover user preferences.
* The user answers questions.
* Only one question is shown at a time.
* The questions shown are dependent on the answers of previous questions 
** For example, One question could be "Do you have any small children that will join you on a hike?"
** The next question could ask for their ages and preferences.
** Of course care must be made to balance the privacy of the users - don't ask for too much information.
* This allows the recommendation engine to discover user preferences.
* The location of the user is important (helps filter out results that are too far away)

A set of possible hikes are then shown to the user.






Idea: show users a gallery of images take on hiking trails in the area, and the user selects the images that look interesting...things that look like a hike they want to go on.






Idea:  User uploads images they have already taken, or selects images they have uploaded to social media.  The recommendation engine analyzes the images, and generates a list of recommendations to the user.






Idea: Generate lists that reflect underlying user types.

Example: 
- 5 family friendly hikes near you
- 5 hikes you can bring your dog
- 5 backpacking trips in the cascades






Idea, show user list of 5-20 popular hikes.  The user selects the hikes that they recognize and or have completed in the past.






Similar to how Facebook works, the idea is that users can create profiles, and add reviews to trails that they hike.  This provides the user their own 'trail guide' of all the hikes that they have done in the past.  It also provides information to the hiking trail recommendation engine of the types of trails that the user has done in the past.






Ask the user to select 5 hikes they have gone on, and then share with their friends.  They add 5 hikes, and then the recommendations are generated from the recommendations of the friends.






''Idea'': Building things that we can put in front of users.  

''Note'': We don't have to build out the entire interface.

Early <--------------> Late

Start early, vet the designs, and go forward

Low Fidelity <----------> High Fidelity

Low Fidelity - Pretty far from complete.


```
Early: Function.   
Middle: Interface.   
Late: Performance.   
```


''Horizontal Prototypes'' -  cover the design as a whole, but in a more shallow way.

''Vertical Prototypes'' - small portion of interaction and prototype it in more detail

''def'' - what is the prototype?

Early <-----------—> Late

* Verbal
* Paper
* Wizard of Oz
* Wireframe
* Physical
* Functional
* Live

Stages of User Activites:

* Establishing the goal
* Forming the intention
* Specifying the action sequence
* Executing the action
* Perceiving the system state
* Interpreting the state
* Evaluating the system state with respect to the goals and intentions.

Part of [[The Design of Everyday Things by Don Norman]]

!! The five whys
Example of root cause analysis for plane crash...

# Q: Why did the Plane crash (A: because it was in an uncontrolled dive)
# Q: Why didn't the pilot recover from the dive? (A: Because the pilot failed to initiate a timely recovery
# Q: Why was that? (A: Because he might have been unconscious (or oxygen deprived)
# Why was that? (A: we don't know, we need to find out)

* Presenting choices with fewer options first then building up to more complex decisions.
* Categorizing items helps prevent overload of the user
* The paradox of choice - more choices mean less action.
* Providing a simple 'Hike of the Week' that changes every week gives something interesting and new each week.
* Ensure no row has more than 5 items
* Filtering
* Providing a default or suggested option
* Social comparison - "most visitors who are similar to your profile choose this option"
* Users take action when effort is small












''Low fidelity drawings ''- easy to modify, but aren't as effective for detailed comprehensive evaluations.

''High Fidelity'' - Good for feedback and evaluation but hard to put together.

''Goal'': Maximize tradeoffs.  Design to get more feedback.






Part of [[The Design of Everyday Things by Don Norman]]

---

Errors have two major forms:

def - ''slips'' - occur when the goal is correct, but the required actions are not done properly.

def - ''action-based slip'': wrong action is performed.  Ex: Pour milk into coffee then put coffee cup in the refrigerator.  Correct action applied to wrong object.

def - ''memory-lapse slip'' - memory fails so the intended action is not done or its results not evaluated.  Ex: Forgetting to turn off the gas burner on stove.

def - ''mistakes'' - occur when the goal or plan is wrong.

def - ''rule-based mistakes'' - person has appropriately diagnosed the situation, but then decided upon an erroneous course of action.

def - ''knowledge based mistake'' - problem is misdiagnosed because of erroneous or incomplete knowledge.  Ex: weight of fuel was computed in pounds instead of kilograms.

def - ''memory lapse mistake'' - forgetting the stages of goals, plans, or evaluations.  Ex: a mechanic failed to complete troubleshooting because of distraction.

!! Errors and the seven stages

* Mistakes (goals and comparing results) happen at higher levels of cognition. Result of conscious deliberations. 
* Slips (execution of plan or perception or interpretation of outcome) occur at lower stages.  Subconscious actions getting waylaid.
* memory lapse can occur at any one of the stages

See Also:

* [[Types of Slips]]
* [[Types of Mistakes]]



[img[Slips vs Errors]]






''Industrial Design''- Creating specifications that optimize the functional value, appearance of products for the mutual benefit of both user and manufacturer.

''Interaction Design'' - Focus on how people interact with technology.  Draws on principles of psychology, art, and emotion to ensure positive emotion.

''Experience Design'' - Designing products, processes, with focus on the quality and enjoyment of the total experience.






Part of [[The Design of Everyday Things by Don Norman]]

---

Many mistakes arise from human thought, often because people tend to rely on remembered experiences.

<<<
retrieval from longterm memory is actually a reconstruction rather than an accurate
record
<<<

def - ''skill based behavior ''- extremely expert at their jobs, so they can do the everyday routine with little or no thought or conscious attention.  Most common error is slips.

def - ''rule based behavior'' - normal routine no longer applicable, but there is a well-prescribed course of action: a rule.  Usually prescribed in the form of if-then statements.  If wrong rule is selected it could be a mistake, if the error occurs during the execution of the rule it is most likely a slip.

def - ''knowledge based behavior'' - when unfamiliar events occur, where neither skills nor rules apply.  There might be considerable reasoning and problem solving.  Conceptual models are essential in guiding development of the plan.

Types of ''rule based mistakes ''

* situation is mistakenly interpreted
* the correct rule is invoked but the rule itself is faulty
* the correct rule is invoked but the outcome is incorrectly evaluated.

<<<
People usually decide by taking the current situation and matching it with something that happened earlier.
<<<

Types of ''knowledge based mistakes''

* required when person encounters an unknown situation
* Best solution is found in translating the appropriate conceptual model.
* In complex situations where help is needed, good procedural manuals can help
* More powerful approach is to develop intelligent computer systems.

The difficulties is usually 

<<<
//__machines do the parts that are easy for people__//, but when the problems become complex, which is precisely when people could use assistance, that is when the __//machines usually fail//__
<<<

Types of ''memory lapse mistakes''

* commonly caused by interruptions.

--> Design to ensure that all relevant information is continuously available.  Far too many designs eliminate all signs of these items once they have been made or acted upon.

--> Social pressures can make people make mistakes

--> Checklists are powerful tools to increase the accuracy of behavior and reduce errors.  Collaboratively followed checklists are essential tools for safety.






Part of [[The Design of Everyday Things by Don Norman]]

----

Slips often __happen more to experts than novices__ since lack of attention to the task.

def - ''Capture Slips'' - instead of desired activity, a more recent (or frequently) performed activity.  Ex: 1.2.3....9,10,Jack, Queen, King.  Partial memory lapse errors.

Designers need to __avoid procedures that have identical opening steps__ but then diverge. Whenever possible,
sequences should be designed to differ from the very start.

def - ''Description Similarity Slip'' - act upon an item similar to the target.  Ex: throwing laundry into toilet instead of basket.

Designers need to __ensure that controls and displays for different purposes are significantly different from each other__.  Airplaine cockpits have controls that are shape encoded so that they both look and feel different.

<<<
....most objects don’t
need precise descriptions, simply enough precision to distinguish
the desired target from alternatives.
<<<

Examples of ''memory slips'':

* Leaving document in photo copier
* Forgetting a child
* Losing a pen
*Using a atm card and leaving it in the machine

Most often memory slips caused by interruptions.

def - ''Mode Error Slip'' - when a device has different states in which the same controls have different meanings (we call these states //modes//)  Ex: Turning off the wrong device in home entertainment systems... happens because we use same control for multiple purposes.

--> Simplifying the control masks the underlying complexity of the use and //pushes the complexity onto the user//.

Mode error is really design error.  They are especially likely when the mode is not visible so the user is expected to remember what mode has been established.

--> Designers must try to avoid modes, but if necessary, equipment must make obvious which mode is invoked.

Describe the interface we have in mind to the user.

Easy to do, hard to do effectively.

Social Desirability Bias.

Ask specific and critical feedback.


<<<
How do we know the user understands the design we are describing?
<<<

Analogies can be powerful tools.






Allowed users to work on their own terms, putting together a "spreadsheet" of figures readily changing the numbers and seeing immediate feedback.

Two factors helped:

* The system was self-contained
* The typical user was a frequent user

Command names were cryptic, not a problem since most users were power users.

Pay no attention to that man behind the curtain.

''idea'': we do the things that the interface would do once it is actually implemented.

User interacts authentically with the system while a human supplies functionality that hasn't yet been implemented.








Xerox 8100 Star Information System - First commercially release computer with GUI with ''W''indows, ''I''cons, ''M''enus, and a ''P''ointing device (WIMP).    

It also supported WYSIWYG interaction.   

Office automation system, shared resources such as printers, file shares using fast ethernet cables.    

Use of the "desktop" metaphor.   

Interactions involved files - "opening a document" rather than "invoke editor".  Files were associated with programs but details were hidden from the user.
